pull_request.title: some minor improvements
pull_request.body:
This pull request introduces several improvements and new features to the codebase, focusing on enhancing the voting experience on questions and replies, improving developer experience with new seeders and factories, updating environment configuration, and adding new styling. The most significant changes include the addition of AJAX support for voting, the creation of database seeders and factories for easier testing and development, and updates to environment and documentation files.

**Voting System Enhancements**
* Added AJAX support to upvote/downvote methods in both `QuestionController` and `ReplyController`, allowing for real-time updates and the ability to remove votes (toggle upvote/downvote), with clear user feedback messages. Also, now tracks the user's vote status for questions and replies. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-6c4cca9be8aad3767012d6cae332e96c81e086135267068b8093914683306f41L74-R92) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-6c4cca9be8aad3767012d6cae332e96c81e086135267068b8093914683306f41L86-R138) [[3]](diffhunk://#diff-6c4cca9be8aad3767012d6cae332e96c81e086135267068b8093914683306f41L113-R184) [[4]](diffhunk://#diff-44c580f97a556bbc32180844fd34a6d51d0708cec590a8d3f34a060d0c04f38fL48-R82) [[5]](diffhunk://#diff-44c580f97a556bbc32180844fd34a6d51d0708cec590a8d3f34a060d0c04f38fL73-R128)
* Reduced the number of most used tags displayed on the question index page from 10 to 5 for better UI clarity.

**Database and Seeding Improvements**
* Added new model factories for `Question`, `Reply`, and `Vote` to simplify the creation of test data. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-f23a86e736f1e9ed0eb300ed668d158f247eac81f8aa5ffa1a416c3a50bc38caR1-R26) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-d847605951895b0c2e1ae8b1c1446fe0e4a7fac20ca8660d7332af8f8d21c357R1-R23) [[3]](diffhunk://#diff-b06c3cb859e1441f0d548c7cc1d7e27019a56896b86d488d54ad327011c26ee6R1-R23)
* Introduced a comprehensive `DummyDataSeeder` for populating the database with sample users, questions, and replies, and updated `DatabaseSeeder` to use it. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-c3757c27404c304baef34c2e2bacd21e7eb3beba8af5e1373d193c187c993e89R1-R89) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-ccad8b4ee6013765c2bc672aa0515f8e99e42949c914cce01e0cb2b4e882775dL16-R16)

**Styling and UI**
* Added a new `resources/css/index.css` file with Tailwind-based and custom styles for improved UI consistency and dark mode support.
* Minor cleanup in `login.css` by removing an unused Google Fonts import.

**Configuration and Documentation Updates**
* Updated `.env.example` to use MySQL instead of SQLite and switched mail settings to use Gmail SMTP for a more realistic development environment. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-a3046da0d15a27e89f2afe639b25748a7ad4d9290af3e7b1b6c1a5533c8f0a8cL22-R27) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-a3046da0d15a27e89f2afe639b25748a7ad4d9290af3e7b1b6c1a5533c8f0a8cL49-R55)
* Improved project setup instructions in `README.md`, including running the queue worker and formatting steps as a numbered list.
* Added the `mallardduck/blade-lucide-icons` package to `composer.json` for icon support.

pull_request.body:
This is a mixed bag.
* A fix for sandbagging runs. In these runs, the metric is the difference between the validation score and the target, hence we always want to minimize the metric. (Which was not the case before this change.)
* I ran new sandbagging experiments, added the new log files and removed the old files. I moved the regular runs to `logs/regular`
* Adjusted plotting code and added new plots
* Removed some files from `.gitattributes`, because they were also covered by wildcards.

This PR contains the following updates:

| Package | Update | Change |

---

### Release Notes

<details>
<summary>tchapi/davis (ghcr.io/tchapi/davis-standalone)</summary>

### [`v5.1.3`](https://redirect.github.com/tchapi/davis/releases/tag/v5.1.3)

[Compare Source](https://redirect.github.com/tchapi/davis/compare/v5.1.2...v5.1.3)

#### What's Changed

- \[Feature] Add calendar public flag option by [@​1Luc1](https://redirect.github.com/1Luc1) in [https://github.com/tchapi/davis/pull/200](https://redirect.github.com/tchapi/davis/pull/200)
- Switch to `bigint` for occurence timestamps in [https://github.com/tchapi/davis/pull/186](https://redirect.github.com/tchapi/davis/pull/186)
- Move docker env vars to .env by [@​eosti](https://redirect.github.com/eosti) in [#​210](https://redirect.github.com/tchapi/davis/issues/210)
- Various other small updates for Docker + documentation

#### How to upgrade

> \[!TIP]
> The added migration will only make changes if you're on MySQL or PostgreSQL; it's expected, you can ignore if you're using SQLite

##### 0. Back up your database

This is a safety precaution in case you end up messing with a migration or the database in general. It's highly recommended, even if you know exactly what you're doing.

##### 1. Update the code and migrate

You can now update the code (*either directly or get the up to date container*), and then run the remaining migrations with:

```
bin/console doctrine:migrations:migrate --allow-no-migration
```

Also, there is a new `PUBLIC_CALENDARS_ENABLED` env var (default to true, maintaining the previous behaviour), check the [README](https://redirect.github.com/tchapi/davis?tab=readme-ov-file#configuration) for more information.

Thanks [@​1Luc1](https://redirect.github.com/1Luc1) for your help

**Full Changelog**: https://github.com/tchapi/davis/compare/v5.1.2...v5.1.3

</details>

issue.body:
## Summary
- scaffold core data structures and traits for complexity scoring
- wire up serde-enabled scoping configuration and supporting tests
- document design decisions and update roadmap

## Testing
- `make check-fmt`
- `make lint`
- `make test`
- `make markdownlint`
- `make nixie`

https://chatgpt.com/codex/tasks/task_e_68a1550541f88322807e4113854bade2

## Summary by Sourcery

Scaffold core API for complexity scoring with foundational data structures, traits, configuration, and tests

New Features:
- Introduce Complexity and Trace structs with serde support and a ComplexityFn trait for query scoring
- Add EmbeddingProvider, DepthEstimator, and AmbiguityEstimator traits for pluggable scoring providers
- Define ScopingConfig enum and VarianceScopingConfig struct with serde-derived configuration loading

Enhancements:
- Expose api, config, and providers modules in lib.rs and re-export key types
- Improve design documentation formatting and mark initial roadmap tasks as completed

Build:
- Add serde, thiserror, serde_json, rstest, and rstest-bdd related dependencies in Cargo.toml

Documentation:
- Refine README example formatting

Tests:
- Add unit tests for API and config serialization
- Implement BDD-style scoring tests using rstest_bdd and feature definitions

**‚ùå Issue 1 - Trait method names**: **Partially addressed through refactoring**
The code has taken a different approach than suggested. Instead of aligning specific method names, it now uses a unified `TextProcessor` trait with a single `process` method:

```rust
pub trait TextProcessor {
    type Output;
    type Error;
    fn process(&self, input: &str) -> Result<Self::Output, Self::Error>;
}

pub type EmbeddingProvider<E> = dyn TextProcessor<Output = Vec<f32>, Error = E>;
pub type DepthEstimator<E> = dyn TextProcessor<Output = f32, Error = E>;
pub type AmbiguityEstimator<E> = dyn TextProcessor<Output = f32, Error = E>;
```

This eliminates the method name confusion entirely, though it's a different solution than originally suggested.

**‚ùå Issue 2 - Error type bounds**: **NOT resolved**
The `Error` associated type still lacks bounds:
```rust
type Error;  // No bounds like `Error: std::error::Error + Send + Sync`
```

**‚ùå Issue 3 - BDD test global state**: **NOT resolved**
The tests still use global mutable state:
```rust
static RESULT: LazyLock<Mutex<Option<Result<Complexity, DummyError>>>> =
    LazyLock::new(|| Mutex::new(None));
```

## Summary
- **1/3 issues** have been addressed (method naming through refactoring)
- **2/3 issues** remain unresolved (error bounds and test isolation)

The remaining issues could be addressed in future iterations to improve code quality and maintainability.
